A lone Ocra Sea Star hunting in a tide pool at Olympic national park, Washington. In 2016 the northern Pacific Ocean experienced temperatures that were notably warmer than normal. This snap change in temp caused a mass die off of sea stars, as well as a host of other small crustaceans. The populations have since had somewhat of a comeback, however, it was a true example of the fragility that occurs from heat index rise.

With wingspans of roughly 5 1/2 feet, Ospreyâ€™s have a very distinguishable and iconic shape. Their wings are incredibly powerful and resilient, allowing them to dive into the water at high velocity, ensnaring large fish and dragging them back to the treetops to feed on. Their hunting success rate is around 70%, a true testament of mastery, and why they can be found on six of the seven continents around the planet.

In 2007 I was hired by @timberland to do a series of ads where they wanted a sense of motion conveyed, without using motion blur. I pitched them on using light streaks to show motion paths, by strapping headlamps to hands and wrists of athletes. This one here was with my friend @joekinder climbing on a bridge near Manitou Springs, CO. To capture this frame we determined the end point of the frame where my flash would fire and freeze the action, which is essentially what frame 3 is. Joe started at the base, and climbed to that point with headlamps on wrists and feet, while I left the shutter open, firing the flash once he hit our established end point. The total exposure time was 94 seconds, leaving behind his light path in a fun way, all done entirely in camera.
